facts.text: On February 3, 1941, the father of the appellants leased the house in dispute to the respondent by a registered deed for 10 years with an option of renewal for further periods as long as the respondent wanted.

anchor.surface_text: On February 3, 1941, by a registered deed the father of the appellants leased to the respondent the house in dispute for a period of 10 years with an option of renewal for further periods for as long as the respondent wanted.

facts.text: The respondent used the house for his hotel.

facts.text: The father of the appellants died on January 25, 1945.

facts.text: Appellants filed suit on December 21, 1945, for declaration that the lease was not for legal necessity or family benefit, alienation not binding, renewal option void, possession, and mesne profits of Rs. 2,655 past and Rs. 250 per month future from December 1, 1945.

anchor.surface_text: On December 21, 1945, the appellants filed a suit for a declaration that the deed of lease of February 3, 1941, executed by their father was number for legal necessity or for the benefit of the family, that the alienation was number binding on them and the option of renewal under the lease was void and unenforceable on account of uncertainty. The appellants further prayed for delivery of possession and for a decree for a sum of Rs. 2,655 as past mesne profits and future mesne profits at Rs. 250 per mensem as from December 1, 1945.

facts.text: Respondent filed written statement on March 11, 1946, and additional on November 26, 1946, raising objection to jurisdiction due to Mysore House Rent Control Order of 1945.

facts.text: High Court on appeal set aside decree, remanded for retrial, holding suit not based on landlord-tenant relationship, s. 8(1) of 1945 Order inapplicable.

anchor.surface_text: On appeal, the High Court set aside the decree on the ground that the nature and scope of the suit had been misconceived by the trial companyrt and that it was number based on relationship of landlord and tenant and therefore s. 8 1  of the Mysore House Rent Control Order was inapplicable and the case was remanded for retrial.

facts.text: Trial court decreed suit on August 23, 1948: lease binding for 10 years from May 1, 1941 due to legal necessity, renewal void for uncertainty, possession decree operative May 1, 1951.

anchor.surface_text: On August 23, 1948, the suit was decreed. The trial companyrt held that the lease was binding for the first period of ten years as from May 1, 1941, as it was supported by legal necessity but the option of renewal was void and unenforceable for uncertainty and therefore a decree for possession was passed to be operative on the expiry of ten years, i.e., May 1, 1951.

facts.text: High Court reversed District Judge's order, directed appellants to return possession and movables to respondent, holding Executing Court lacked jurisdiction due to Mysore House Rent and Accommodation Control Order, 1948.

anchor.surface_text: An appeal was taken to the High Court and it reversed the order of the Executing Court and directed the appellants to return possession of the house in dispute to the respondent along with the moveables which were in the house at the time respondent was evicted. anchor.surface_text: The question for decision mainly turns upon the applicability of the provisions of the two House Rent Control Orders of 1945 and 1948 and how far they were applicable to the proceedings in the suit and execution.

holdings.text: The Mysore House Rent Control Order of 1948 was not repugnant to the Transfer of Property Act and continued in force as an existing law saved by Article 372 of the Constitution, applicable to the execution proceedings in July 1951.

anchor.surface_text: The argument, therefore, that as from April 1, 1951, as a result of repugnancy the House Rent Control Order of 1948 stood repealed must be repelled as unsound and cannot be sustained, because it was an existing law which was saved by art. 372 of the Constitution and remained unaffected by art.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Part B States Laws Act 1951 did not automatically extend TP Act to Mysore until notification on Sep 12, 1951 effective Oct 1, 1951; 1948 Order was existing law continued by Art 372; cites Punjab HC on similar effect.

holdings.text: Section 47 CPC applies to the execution proceedings as the question relates to execution, discharge and satisfaction of the decree.

anchor.surface_text: The inapplicability of s. 47 to the proceedings out of which the appeal has arisen was also raised before us, but that contention is equally unsubstantial because the question whether the decree was completely satisfied and therefore the court became functus officio is a matter relating to execution, satisfaction and discharge of the decree.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Objection to execution not warranted by decree terms falls under s.47; cites SC precedent Ramanna v. Nallaparaju.

holdings.text: Res judicata does not bar the respondent from objecting to executability of the decree on grounds of the 1948 Rent Control Order.

anchor.surface_text: The plea of res judicata is not available to the appellants as the prohibition on account of the House Rent Control Order was not against the passing of the decree but against its execution and therefore the objection to the executability could only be taken at the time of the execution of the decree

holdings.reasoning_summary: Earlier plea and decision concerned jurisdiction to pass decree under 1945 Order; execution objection under 1948 Order raisable separately at execution stage.

holdings.text: Neither waiver nor estoppel applies against the statutory prohibition on execution of the eviction decree.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Lawyer's letter promising arrangements is slender basis; no detrimental reliance; estoppel unavailable against statute.

holdings.text: Sections 9(1) and 16 of the 1948 Order impose a fetter on the Executing Court's power to execute an eviction decree without Controller's certificate, amounting to lack of jurisdiction rather than mere error.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Provisions restrict executability itself, limiting court power; not discretionary error.
